a new parent

new parent, making the screenshot parallel to all the widgets of a

page.

entry.title: [Safe Browsing] Refactor protego ping logging logic
entry.content:
The logic to record the most recent protego ping value was implicitly

dependent on whether the preference service had been provided to the url

lookup service. For now, this worked because the enterprise version of

the service did not provide a the preference service. This was brittle,

however, because if someone decided to supply a preference service to

the `ChromeEnterpriseRealTimeUrlLookupService`, they would inadvertently

cause that service to start logging protego pings.



To make this code more robust, we introduce a new virtual method that

the base class provides an empty implementation for. Then any sub-class

that wants to implement the functionality can do so. In this case, we

moved the implementation to the `RealTimeUrlLookupService` class.

entry.title: Handle OOFs in spanners within NGOutOfFlowLayoutPart::ReplaceFragment
entry.content:
When we find an OOF in the CB path within

NGOutOfFlowLayoutPart::ReplaceFragment(), we end up looking for the

next viable fragmentation context root to search for its fragment(s).

However, if there is a spanner in the CB path (as a result of

CL:3343283), that OOF will propagate up to the next context since

spanners are not laid out in their immediate multicol parent.



Thus, we will need to continue up the tree in such cases in

NGOutOfFlowLayoutPart::ReplaceFragment() in order to properly find

the OOF ancestor in question.

truth, and knows about the samples for all sparse histograms. A sparse

histogram may request its own "PersistentSampleMapRecords" from the

"data manager", which basically just replicates the "data manager"

as needed.



This refactoring should have practically no performance penalties,

neither in terms of time nor space (maybe just a tiny bit more space,

but this is trivial). This is not a no-op -- the restriction for only

one SparseHistogram instance per histogram is now gone.



Also updates various tests (threadsafe, allocator, subprocess) to

make sure this works properly. These updated tests fail without

these changes, and pass with the changes.

entry.title: [iOS] Fix ordering of overflow menu model initialization calls
entry.content:
This was causing a small bug where feature-provided badges weren't being

cleared because that happens as part of the call to

`-reorderDestinationsForInitialMenu`, but during `-updateModel`, the

badges were being added to the destinations, so once the reorder call

came around, the orderer thought that the badges were still there.



This CL fixes that by splitting `-updateModel` up into two parts, one

to update the state of the individual items (which can then be called

before the initial reorder), and one to update any other orderings (e.g.

order of actions, order of other groups), which can be called

afterwards.

entry.title: Adjust editor menu promo card bounds.
entry.content:
Make some adjustments to EditorMenuPromoCardView's bounds to better

reflect the specs:



1. Set the min width and max width according to the specs.



2. Add some logic to adjust the promo card position if is horizontally

offscreen.



3. Use longer placeholder text for the description so that we can check

multiline text is sized correctly. (E.g. this surfaces an issue with

resizing the multiline label similar to crbug.com/c/678337. Issue

seems hard to fix so we add a workaround by explicitly setting the

labels' maximum width.)



Logic for adjusting the promo card position is not perfect yet, e.g. if

anchor view is very tall, then placing the promo card above or below

will both place the promo card partially offscreen. But, it should be

good enough for now. In a followup, consider improving the logic and

also refactoring so that some UpdateBounds logic can be shared with

EditorMenuView (b:297296089).

> onBeforeRequest action for a single declarativeNetRequest ruleset.

> since histograms only allow the emission of a single data point, we

> 1,000 - 10,000

> 0 - 15

> 15 - 100

> 100 - 500

> 500+

> taken to evaluate regex rules.

entry.title: Use clang's built-in verify mode for implementing nocompile tests.
entry.content:
This CL also ports one existing nocompile test to the new format for

validation purposes.



Using clang's verify mode has several advantages:

- the nocompile driver no longer has to multiplex commpiler jobs; it is

largely just a pass through to invoke clang with some additional logic

for handling /showIncludes -> depfile mapping (on Windows) and

generating a placeholder .o file.

- the nocompile driver no longer has to generate a smoke test to verify

that the nocompile driver is working correctly

- test runtime no longer has O(n^2) scaling; each nocompile test just

takes a single pass now, no matter how many test cases it contains.

- the expectations are easier to read: they no longer default to regexp

matching, which often had the accidental side effect of any

expectation with `||` matching anything.

- easier-to-read nocompile test failures: they show up as regular clang

errors instead of wrapping each line of stderr from a failing

nocompile run in #pragma error.

- the nocompile tests no longer generate an executable binary; instead,

regular unit tests can simply depend on them directly. This simplifies

buildbot configuration, since the nocompile tests no longer need to be

specified as additional compile targets.



In addition, this CL updates the nocompile templates to take advantage

of the fact that variables like cflags, et cetera are now available in

custom actions, reducing the number of compiler flags the nocompile

driver needs to manually manage. This allows nocompile test coverage to

be expanded by default to cover any clang builder.

entry.title: Add {{#}} & {{/}} syntax for ChildNodeParts
entry.content:
This CL enables this syntax:





before {{#}} inside {{/}} after





The above snippet will now replace the {{}} parts with empty comment

nodes, and a `ChildNodePart` will be attached that surrounds "inside".



Note the new `parseparts` attribute, which is the opt-in for this

new behavior (in addition to the required runtime flag being enabled

of course).



The implementation looks like this:

- The `HTMLElementStack` gets a new `parse_parts_count_` which keeps

a count of the `parseparts` attributes seen on elements. Currently,

`parseparts` is strictly an opt-in, and subsequent `parseparts`

can't be used to somehow opt back out.

- The `HTMLTreeBuilder` relays to the `HTMLTokenizer` whether or not

we're currently inside a `parseparts` scope.

- The `HTMLToken` and `AtomicHTMLToken` classes get a new token type,

`kDOMPart` which is used for the ChildNodePart node endpoint

markers. These have a DOMPartTokenType which is either

`kChildNodePartStart` or `kChildNodePartEnd`.

- The `HTMLTokenizer` looks for `{{#}}` and `{{/}}` in the data

state, and if detected, switches to two new tokenizer states,

`kChildNodePartStartState` and `kChildNodePartEndState`. Those both

immediately emit a `kDOMPart` token and return to the DATA state.

- The `HTMLTreeBuilder`, when it finds a `kDOMPart` token, forwards

it to `HTMLConstructionSite::InsertDOMPart()`.

- `HTMLConstructionSite::InsertDOMPart()` adds the ChildNodePart via

the existing mechanism.



I split the one test file into multiple, and basically copy/pasted

the "old" declarative style into a new test. Eventually/soon I will

delete the old style (e.g. ``) syntax support, and

the old test with it.



NodeParts aren't yet supported.

entry.title: [Extensions] Add DNR metrics on per-ruleset evaluation time
entry.content:
Add metrics on the amount of time it takes to evaluate the

onBeforeRequest action for a single declarativeNetRequest ruleset.

Since this is (inherently) going to be dependent on ruleset size, and

since histograms only allow the emission of a single data point, we

add metrics for different buckets of rule counts:



0 - 1,000

1,000 - 10,000

10,000 - 30,000

30,000 - 100,000

100,000 - 300,000

300,000+



We also add metrics for the evaluation of regex rules, which we expect

to take a significant amount of time. These are bucketed into:



0 - 15

15 - 100

100 - 500

500+



Finally, we add an unbucketed metric for the percentage of total time

taken to evaluate regex rules.



These metrics will help us evaluate the impact of extensions specifying

many enabled rulesets.
